Filter a CSV
Data.feed({
    source: "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/emergenzeHack/terremotocentro/master/data/issues.csv",
    type:   "csv"
}).load(function (mydata) {
    var facebookIssues = mydata.select('WHERE labels like "Facebook"');
    console.log(facebookIssues.column("id").values());
}).error(function (e) {
    console.error(e);
});

Pivot election results
Data.feed({ source: scrutiniUrl, type: "csv" }).load(function (scrutini) {
    var pivot = scrutini.pivot({
        lead:  "codice",
        keep:  ["tipo"],
        sum:   ["membri"],
        cols:  "descr_lista",
        value: "voti"
    });
    console.log(pivot.columnNames());
});

Load a remote GeoParquet file by bounding box
Data.feed({
    source:  "https://s3.eubucco.com/eubucco/v0.2/buildings/parquet/nuts_id=ITC4/ITC4.parquet",
    type:    "parquet",
    bbox:    [9.185, 45.460, 9.198, 45.468],
    columns: ["id", "subtype", "height"],
    maxRows: 50000
}).load(function (mydata) {
    console.log(mydata.records.length + " buildings in view");
}).error(function (e) {
    console.error(e);
});
See Remote Parquet by Bounding Box for how CRS reprojection and the options work.

Load three CSVs in parallel
Data.provider()
    .addSource("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ondata/elezionipolitiche2018/master/dati/scrutiniCI_cm.csv", "csv")
    .addSource("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ondata/elezionipolitiche2018/master/risorse/comuniViminaleISTAT.csv", "csv")
    .addSource("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ondata/elezionipolitiche2018/master/dati/camera_geopolitico_italia.csv", "csv")
    .load(function (dataA) {
        var scrutini = dataA[0].select('WHERE tipo_riga == "LI"');
        console.log(scrutini.columnNames());
    });

Join two already-loaded tables
new Data.Merger()
    .addSource(prezzi,   { lookup: "idImpianto", columns: ["descCarburante", "prezzo", "isSelf", "dtComu"] })
    .addSource(impianti, { lookup: "idImpianto", columns: ["Bandiera", "Latitudine", "Longitudine"] })
    .realize(function (mergedTable) {
        console.log(mergedTable.columnNames());
    });

Ran into something these don’t cover? Check Troubleshooting.

Filtering rows: select(query)
select() takes a small SQL-like WHERE string and returns a new Data.Table with the matching rows:
var facebookIssues = mydata.select('WHERE labels like "Facebook"');

var overThreshold = rawdata.select('WHERE "Age" = "Total" AND "SEX" = "MW" AND "Series" = "Labour force participation rate"');

var workingAge = rawdata.select('WHERE "Age" BETWEEN "18" AND "65"');
Supported operators: =, &lt;&gt; (not equal), &gt;, &lt;, &gt;=, &lt;=, BETWEEN ... AND ..., LIKE, NOT, IN "v1,v2,v3". Combine conditions with AND / OR.

Reading a column
.column(name) returns a Data.Column handle — see its methods below, most commonly .values():
var ids = mydata.column("id").values();
var uniqueLabels = mydata.column("labels").uniqueValues();

Building a pivot table: pivot(options)
var pivot = scrutini.pivot({
    lead:  "codice",           // row-defining field(s)
    keep:  ["tipo"],           // columns copied straight through
    sum:   ["membri"],         // columns summed per lead group
    cols:  "descr_lista",      // this field's unique values become new columns
    value: "voti"              // values accumulated into those new columns
});
pivot() always adds a Total column. If you need specific pivot columns to exist even when no rows match them (pre-seeded with 0), pass forced: [...] with the column names.

Summarizing: aggregate(valueColumn, groupColumns)
Sums (or averages, with calc: "mean") a value column, grouped by one or more pipe-separated columns:
var totalsByRegion = mydata.aggregate("population", "region");
var totalsByRegionAndYear = mydata.aggregate("population", "region|year");

Collapsing duplicates: condense(leadColumn, options)
Collapses rows that share the same value in leadColumn, summing (or calc: "max"-ing) numeric columns not listed in keep:
var perStation = readings.condense("stationId", { keep: ["name", "lat", "lng"] });

Filtering with a callback: filter(callback)
For conditions select()’s query string can’t express, pass a plain function returning truthy/falsy per row:
var recent = mydata.filter(function (row) {
    return row[dateColIndex] &gt; cutoffTimestamp;
});

Deriving a new column: addColumn(options, callback)
mydata.addColumn({ source: "height", destination: "heightFt" }, function (heightM) {
    return heightM * 3.28084;
});

// no source: callback receives the whole row
mydata.addColumn({ destination: "summary" }, function (row) {
    return row.join(" / ");
});

Data.feed(options) — load from a URL
The main entry point. Fetches from a URL and is always asynchronous:
Data.feed({ source: szUrl, type: "csv" }).load(function (mydata) {
    // mydata is a Data.Table
}).error(function (e) {
    // handle the failure
});
Use this whenever your data lives at a URL — which is the common case.

Data.object(options) — load from data you already have
Same idea, but source is a JavaScript value you already hold in memory (e.g. the body of a response you fetched yourself), not a URL. Still asynchronous — call .import() with a callback:
Data.object({ source: response, type: "json" }).import(function (mydata) {
    // mydata is a Data.Table
});
For binary formats (parquet, geoparquet, gpkg, flatgeobuf, geobuf) source must already be an ArrayBuffer — Data.object does no fetching for these, it only parses what you hand it.

Data.import(options) — synchronous shortcut
A synchronous convenience wrapper around Data.object:
var table = Data.import({ source: response, type: "json" });
var ids = table.column("id").values();






ImportantOnly safe for synchronous parsers



Data.import() returns immediately — there’s no callback, no .load()/.import() to wait on. It works for parsers that run synchronously (json, csv, geojson, and similar), but returns undefined for anything genuinely asynchronous (e.g. jsonstat, which lazy-loads its own parser script). If you’re not sure, use Data.object(...).import(callback) instead.

Step 1: Include the library
Create an HTML file and include data.js from the CDN — no build step, no other dependencies required for CSV/JSON:
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;My First data.js query&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/gjrichter/data.js/data.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;script&gt;
        // your code goes here
    &lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

Step 2: Load a dataset
The entry point for loading from a URL is Data.feed(). It’s asynchronous — pass a callback to .load():
Data.feed({
    source: "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/emergenzeHack/terremotocentro/master/data/issues.csv",
    type:   "csv"
}).load(function (mydata) {
    // mydata is a Data.Table — the whole dataset is available here
    console.log(mydata.columnNames());
}).error(function (e) {
    console.error("load failed:", e);
});






Notesource has a few aliases



Data.feed() also accepts src, url, or ext in place of source — whichever is present first wins. source is the clearest name to use in new code.

Step 3: Filter and read the result
Once loaded, mydata is a Data.Table. Use .select() with a small SQL-like WHERE string to filter rows, and .column(name).values() to pull out a plain array:
Data.feed({
    source: "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/emergenzeHack/terremotocentro/master/data/issues.csv",
    type:   "csv"
}).load(function (mydata) {
    // filter to rows where the "labels" column mentions Facebook
    var facebookIssues = mydata.select('WHERE labels like "Facebook"');

    // pull all values of one column into a plain array
    var ids = facebookIssues.column("id").values();

    console.log(ids.length + " matching issues:", ids);
});
That’s the whole loop: load → filter → read. From here:

Loading Data covers every supported source type (JSON, GeoJSON, Parquet, GeoPackage, and more) and the three ways to load data (Data.feed, Data.object, Data.import).
Transforming Tables covers the full select() syntax plus pivot(), aggregate(), sort() and friends.
Remote Parquet by Bounding Box if you’re working with large GeoParquet files and only want the rows in view.


Ready for more? Continue to Loading Data.

Basic usage
Data.feed({
    source:  "https://s3.eubucco.com/eubucco/v0.2/buildings/parquet/nuts_id=ITC4/ITC4.parquet",
    type:    "parquet",
    bbox:    [9.185, 45.460, 9.198, 45.468],   // [minX, minY, maxX, maxY], always EPSG:4326
    columns: ["id", "subtype", "height"]
}).load(function (mydata) {
    console.log(mydata.records.length + " buildings in view");
}).error(function (e) {
    console.error(e);
});
bbox is always [minX, minY, maxX, maxY] in EPSG:4326 (plain lon/lat), regardless of what coordinate system the source file itself uses — data.js handles the reprojection (see below).

Guarding against huge result sets
A bbox drawn too wide over a dense area can still select a very large number of rows. Use maxRows to fail fast instead of stalling on a huge transfer and an expensive client-side geometry decode:
Data.feed({
    source:  someUrl,
    type:    "parquet",
    bbox:    currentViewportBbox,
    maxRows: 50000
}).load(function (mydata) { ... })
  .error(function (e) {
    // e.g. "bbox selects 128340 rows (limit 50000) - zoom in or raise maxRows"
    console.warn(e);
});

Data.provider(): load several sources in parallel
Data.provider()
    .addSource("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ondata/elezionipolitiche2018/master/dati/scrutiniCI_cm.csv", "csv")
    .addSource("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ondata/elezionipolitiche2018/master/risorse/comuniViminaleISTAT.csv", "csv")
    .addSource("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ondata/elezionipolitiche2018/master/dati/camera_geopolitico_italia.csv", "csv")
    .load(function (dataA) {
        var scrutini = dataA[0];
        var comuniViminaleISTAT = dataA[1];
        var cameraGeopoliticoItalia = dataA[2];

        scrutini = scrutini.select('WHERE tipo_riga == "LI"');
        // ... continue working with all three tables
    });
load(callback) fires once with an array of Data.Table, in the same order you called addSource. Use .error(handler) for a shared load-failure handler, and .notify(handler) if you want a progress callback as each source starts/finishes.






Note.load() is an alias for .realize()



Both names fire the same way — .load() matches Data.feed(...).load(callback)’s naming and is the one to reach for in new code. .realize() is the older name and still works exactly the same.








NoteData.provider() is the preferred name — Data.Broker is the older one



Data.provider() and Data.broker() are two names for the same thing — both return a Data.Broker instance. Data.provider() is the name to reach for in new code; Data.Broker/Data.broker() still work and show up in older examples and in some internal method names (Data.Feed.prototype.broker()), but are the legacy naming.








ImportantDoesn’t inherit Data.Table/Data.Feed methods



Despite an internal comment suggesting otherwise, a Data.provider() instance doesn’t expose .select()/.column() directly — work with the individual tables in the .load() callback’s array instead.

Data.Merger: join already-loaded tables
Use this once you have two or more Data.Tables (from separate Data.feed() calls, or from a Data.provider()) and want to combine them by a shared key:
var merger = new Data.Merger()
    .addSource(prezzi,   { lookup: "idImpianto", columns: ["descCarburante", "prezzo", "isSelf", "dtComu"] })
    .addSource(impianti, { lookup: "idImpianto", columns: ["Bandiera", "Latitudine", "Longitudine"] });

merger.realize(function (mergedTable) {
    var selection = mergedTable.select('WHERE tipo_riga == "LI"');
    // ... continue working with the merged table
});
The first addSource call provides the row backbone; every subsequent source is looked up by matching lookup values and its columns are added alongside. label (optional, in the same addSource options object) lets you rename incoming columns; setOutputColumns([...]) afterwards restricts/orders the final table to specific columns.









Data.provider()
Data.Merger




Input
URLs (loads them itself)
Already-loaded Data.Tables (or plain 2D arrays)


Combines by
Nothing — just returns all tables together
A shared lookup key, join-style


Use when
You need several independent datasets loaded before continuing
You need to enrich one table’s rows with columns from another




